Preheat your oven to 200°C and put a large #saucepan{} of water on to boil for the tomato. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Peel the @ginger{1/2}(peeled and grated) too. Halve, peel and finely chop the @onion{1/2}(peeled and finely chopped). Cut the @new potatoes{1}(cut in half). Roughly chop the @coriander{2}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Put the potatoes on a #baking tray{} and drizzle over some @olive oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and toss to coat. Pop on the top shelf of your oven. Roast until crispy, ~{25%minutes}.

> TIP: Shake the baking tray halfway through so they cook evenly.

Pop the @vine tomatoes{2} in your pan of boiling water for ~{1%minute} then drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water. Peel the skin from the tomato - the dip in the boiling water should make this easy. Chop into 1/2cm cubes. This is a concasse!

Put a splash of @olive oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-low heat. Add the onion. Cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Add the garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute} more. Add the tomato, turn the heat to low and let it simmer very gently for ~{15%minutes}.

> TIP: If it starts to dry out, add a splash of water.

Put a splash of @oil{} in another frying pan, this time on medium-high heat. Season the @sea bass fillets{2} on both sides with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and place it in the pan, skin-side down. Cook until the skin has crisped up, ~{2%minutes}. Turn carefully and cook the other side, ~{3%minutes}. Add a knob of @?butter{} and a squeeze of @lime{1/2}(juiced) to the pan then remove from the heat.

> TIP: The fish is cooked when the centre is opaque.

Add the ginger, @fish sauce{1}(bit by bit to taste) and half the coriander to the tomato concasse. Serve your sea bass fillets with some crispy potatoes on the side and a generous amount of tomato concasse spooned over the top. Finish with a sprinkle of the remaining coriander. Enjoy!